.TH "RRIP_CLI" "1" "2026-06-10" "" "User Commands"
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
rrip_cli - secure audio CD ripper, command-line interface
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]rrip_cli\f[R] [\f[B]-V\f[R]] [\f[B]-f\f[R] \f[I]FILE\f[R]]
[\f[B]-v\f[R]] [\f[B]-c\f[R]] [\f[B]-d\f[R]] [\f[B]-B\f[R]]
[\f[B]-h\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]rrip_cli\f[R] is the command-line interface of Rubyripper, a secure
audio CD ripper inspired by Exact Audio Copy (EAC).
It uses \f[B]cdparanoia\f[R](1) in a sophisticated way to ensure
accurate rips: each track is ripped multiple times and the results
compared chunk by chunk to detect and correct read errors.
.PP
When launched without \f[B]-d\f[R], \f[B]rrip_cli\f[R] presents an
interactive text menu allowing the user to review disc metadata, select
tracks, and configure all ripping parameters before starting.
.SS Interactive menus
.PP
The main menu provides access to five preference categories:
.TP
\f[B]Secure ripping\f[R]
Drive device path, drive read offset, missing sample padding, extra
cdparanoia parameters, required chunk matches (normal and erroneous),
maximum rip attempts, automatic disc ejection after ripping, and log
file policy.
.TP
\f[B]TOC analysis\f[R]
Cuesheet generation, single-file (image) rip mode, hidden audio sector
ripping, pre-gap handling (prepend or append), and pre-emphasis
correction (cuesheet tag or sox processing).
.TP
\f[B]Codecs\f[R]
Enable/disable and configure encoding options for FLAC, Ogg Vorbis
(oggenc), MP3 (LAME), AAC (Nero), AAC (Fraunhofer), WavPack, Opus, WAV,
and any external encoder.
Also controls playlist generation, maximum encoding threads, and audio
normalisation (replaygain or normalize).
.TP
\f[B]Metadata\f[R]
Choice of metadata provider (none, GnuDB, or MusicBrainz), GnuDB server
and credentials, and MusicBrainz country/date preferences.
.TP
\f[B]Other\f[R]
Output base directory, file naming schemes for normal albums,
various-artist albums, and single-file rips (using substitution
variables \f[B]%a\f[R] artist, \f[B]%b\f[R] album, \f[B]%g\f[R] genre,
\f[B]%y\f[R] year, \f[B]%f\f[R] codec, \f[B]%n\f[R] track number,
\f[B]%t\f[R] track title, \f[B]%va\f[R] various artist).
Also configures log viewer, file manager, and verbose/debug modes.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]-V\f[R], \f[B]--version\f[R]
Print the current version of Rubyripper and exit.
.TP
\f[B]-f\f[R] \f[I]FILE\f[R], \f[B]--file\f[R] \f[I]FILE\f[R]
Load preferences from \f[I]FILE\f[R] instead of the default
configuration file.
If the file does not exist, default preferences are used and a warning
is printed.
.TP
\f[B]-v\f[R], \f[B]--verbose\f[R]
Enable verbose output during ripping and encoding.
.TP
\f[B]-c\f[R], \f[B]--configure\f[R]
Open the interactive preferences menu on startup, before scanning the
disc.
.TP
\f[B]-d\f[R], \f[B]--defaults\f[R]
Skip all interactive menus and start ripping immediately using the
current preferences.
.TP
\f[B]-B\f[R], \f[B]--batch\f[R]
Exit automatically once the rip is complete.
Useful in combination with \f[B]-d\f[R] for unattended operation.
.TP
\f[B]-h\f[R], \f[B]--help\f[R]
Print a usage summary and exit.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/rubyripper/settings\f[R]
User configuration file (defaults to
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/rubyripper/settings\f[R] when
\f[B]XDG_CONFIG_HOME\f[R] is not set).
Created on first run.
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
\f[B]rrip_gui\f[R](1), \f[B]cdparanoia\f[R](1), \f[B]flac\f[R](1),
\f[B]oggenc\f[R](1), \f[B]lame\f[R](1)
.SH AUTHOR
.PP
Rubyripper was written by Bouke Woudstra and is maintained at
<https://github.com/bleskodev/rubyripper>.
.PP
